      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "To dampen these forms of speculation, both Vancouver and the province of British Columbia have introduced new forms of taxation. In British Columbia, empty residences owned by foreign nationals, and other “satellite families” based primarily in other countries and not paying local taxes, are subject to a “speculation and vacancy tax” of 2% of assessed value.¹ In addition, non-primary residences in Vancouver, British Columbia that sit empty for more than six months are charged an “empty homes tax” equal to 1% of their assessed value.² These taxes create a strong disincentive against “parking” and speculating on local real estate.",
